<TEXT>
el salvadors leftist rebels opened their 
first peace talks in two years with government representatives 
wednesday by offering to end their civil war and reorganize as a 
political party in exchange for reforms 
it was the first time the rebel farabundo marti national 
liberation front said it would participate in the political process 
as part of the path toward peace 
the rebel plan called for the civil war to end in six months 
there is a very good climate said gregorio rosa chavez 
auxiliary bishop of san salvador who is observing the talks he 
said the government also made a proposal but he refused to discuss 
it 
after mondays session ended salvadoran justice minister oscar 
alfredo santamaria told a news conference the talks were held in a 
positive atmosphere 
we feel satisfied he said of progress made 
santamaria said the government proposed it meet rebel 
representatives for two days every two months with the roman 
catholic church acting as observer and not as mediator 
he was reluctant to predict any outcome 
what will happen i dont know santamaria said 
farabundo marti leaders outlined their plan in a statement before 
talks opened to end the decadeold war that has cost more than 
70000 lives aside from the political participation offer little 
in it was new 
the guerrillas demanded that president alfredo cristianis 
rightist administration reform the judiciary prosecute human rights 
violators and end all political repression and undertake 
constitutional and land reforms 
they proposed that ultrarightists be weeded out of the judicial 
system and the military now made up of 56000 soldiers be 
restructured and cut down 
they also asked the government to move up the date of el 
salvadors 1991 legislative and municipal elections and allow them 
to participate as a party 
in exchange the guerrillas said they would agree to a ceasefire 
starting no later than nov 15 and would begin to integrate 
themselves into el salvadors political life 
we are not negotiating from a position of weakness said 
joaquin villalobos a senior guerrilla leader 
he said the talks will test the cristiani administrations desire 
for peace 
cristiani refused to answer questions at a brief public 
appearance in san salvador 
miguel saenz a rebel spokesman told reporters the participants 
began by discussing procedural matters and an agenda 
many rebel demands similar to those made wednesday were rejected 
by the rightistdominated military in three previous negotiating 
sessions from 1984 to 1987 
villalobos said wednesday that the rebels want a quick end to the 
war he said the salvadoran people are tired of fighting we are 
conscious the war has to end 
many of the victims of the war against a succession of 
usbacked governments have been civilians 
after a ceasefire and government recognition of the rebels as a 
political party a lasting peace would be negotiated with the front 
laying down its arms villalobos said 
cristiani invited the guerrillas to lay down their arms and 
engage in peace talks when he succeeded president jose napoleon 
duarte for a fiveyear term june 1 
rebel and government called a temporary ceasefire for the 
twoday peace talks 
the government said earlier it will not negotiate a reduction in 
the military and that if the rebels want reform they should pursue 
it through the political process 
the rebels boycotted regular elections since 1982 saying such 
elections offer only a veneer of democracy 
</TEXT>
