<TEXT>
the great plains are agriculturally obsolete 
and bound to revert to the tall grasses and the buffalo claim two 
researchers the only question left they say is whether the 
transformation will be eased by government or imposed by brute 
market forces 
frank j popper and deborah epstein popper he heads the urban 
affairs department at rutgers the state university of new jersey 
and she teaches geography there believe that about one more 
generation can support itself by farming on the great plains before 
vast stretches of 10 states are simply abandoned 
as might be imagined their view is none too welcome in the area 
the nuttiest ideas never seem to die is what a fargo nd 
forum editorial said 
but the poppers insist it was a mistake to break the sod in the 
first place a historic error fostered by the 1862 homestead act 
which gave 160 acres to anyone willing to settle the land and stay 
five years 
the poppers first spelled out their idea in an article in 
planning magazine published by the american planning association 
and elaborated on it in telephone interviews 
they wrote 
we believe that over the next generation the plains will as a 
result of the largest longestrunning agricultural and 
environmental miscalculation in america become almost totally 
depopulated 
they described the area from the 98th meridian west to the 
rockies as endlessly windswept nearly treeless semiarid 
austerely beautiful historically untenable increasingly empty and 
now facing ecological devastation 
ultimately they predict about a third to half the land of the 
10 states most of the dakotas the western twothirds of nebraska 
the western halves of kansas oklahoma and texas the eastern tips 
of new mexico and colorado eastern wyoming and all but westernmost 
montana will return to its prewhite condition 
they figure the process will take 20 to 30 years 
service center cities such as bismarck nd and cheyenne 
wyo or towns near interstate highways might stay in business so 
would a few locales able to sustain themselves through agriculture 
energy development or tourism the poppers say 
only government subsidies make farming viable now and the 
subsidies are bound to vanish in an era of budget deficits and farm 
surpluses they say 
they propose having the government gradually buy back farmland 
and tear down the fences replant the shortgrass and restock the 
animals including many bison creating what we would call the 
buffalo commons 
although theyve met with hostility from the plains some find 
truth in what they say 
i agree with frank that it was a miscalculation when the social 
engineers put as many people as they did out here through that 
homestead act says rancher jim strain of rapid city sd who 
runs the american cowmans association 
i think it was meant to be a vast grasslands for producers of 
redmeat animals to graze their herds on it was a mistake to plow 
this land with its limited topsoil and limited moisture 
and geographer bret wallach of the university of oklahoma said 
the poppers are a bit quixotic in the short term but in the long 
run it is an idea whose time will probably come 
countries in the third world are going to be able to take care 
of themselves one of these days he says farm productivity will 
keep increasing and markets wont grow indefinitely and so you have 
a question of more and more surplus land in new england they let 
the farmland grow back into trees and maybe that is the enlightened 
thing to do restore it to its virgin use 
