tibetan courts have sentenced 10 people buddhist 
monks among them to prison terms of up to life on charges of 
rioting and spying for the dalai lama during an antichinese 
uprising in march china said today 
the official xinhua news agency said an intermediate court in the 
tibetan capital of lhasa on sentenced passang to life imprisonment 
for beating smashing looting and burning during the threeday 
disturbance in which 16 people were killed by official count 
tibetans said between 20 and 30 died 
xinhua said cering ngoizhu 57 was given a 12year prison term 
for inciting young people to sing tibetan independence songs and 
participate in the disturbances 
it said three men were convicted of spying for the dalai lama 
clique a reference to supporters of tibets former spiritual 
leader who fled to india with the dalai lama following a failed 1959 
uprising against the chinese army 
one man ngoizhu was sentenced to 11 years for spying and two 
others both former lamas or monks in lhasa were given fiveyear 
terms for collecting information about the march uprising for the 
dalai lama the agency said 
two other monks were sent to prison for four and three years for 
hanging the banned tibetan flag in their monastery and shouting 
reactionary slogans during the demonstrations xinhua said three 
more men received sentences of up to eight years for looting and 
destruction of property 
the dispatch said all 10 men were sentenced on tuesday but did 
not say when or where they were convicted 
in july the lhasa intermediate court sentenced 10 other men to 
lighter terms for counterrevolutionary activities during the 
riots 
china declared martial law in lhasa on march 8 and arrested 
hundreds of participants in the demonstrations 
martial law is still in force and foreign journalists are still 
barred from visiting the city there has been some relaxation on 
visits by foreign tourists a major source of revenue for the 
impoverished mountain area with approved groups of three or more 
now allowed into lhasa 
the violent clash with chinese security forces was the fourth 
major proindependence disturbance in lhasa since september 1987 
many tibetans reject chinese claims that tibet has been part of 
china for 700 years and are resentful of past suppression of 
tibetan religion and culture 
the dalai lama has suggested that tibet be granted selfautonomy 
