<TEXT>
police today arrested a man they said organized a 
still unexplained effort to sell uranium to the us embassy in 
tokyo officials said 
so far nine people have been arrested in the case on charges of 
illegally handling the radioactive element 
japanese law requires special authorization to handle the 
element which can be used in nuclear power generation and to make 
nuclear weapons 
investigators still have not learned where those involved 
obtained the uranium or why they tried to sell it to the embassy for 
more than 2000 times its market price of 275 an ounce said an 
official of the tokyo metropolitan police department 
the official speaking on condition of anonymity identified the 
last of those arrested as kouki tomoda 51 an antique art dealer 
and former underworld gang member from yamatotakada in nara 
prefecture southwestern japan 
tomoda arrested at a tokyo hotel had been on a wanted list 
since sunday when police seized 88 pounds of uranium from an 
acquaintance of his in kurume fukuoka prefecture about 560 miles 
southwest of tokyo 
the acquaintance a food dealer identified as masateru yuwasaki 
41 also has been arrested the official said 
he said tomoda was suspected of having sold a capsule containing 
36 ounces of refined natural uranium to masao kikuchi 54 a former 
veterinarian for about 55000 in june kikuchi also is among those 
arrested 
police said the group took this sample to the us embassy on 
aug 8 and proposed to sell another 88 pounds for 83 million 
a us embassy official speaking on condition of anonymity said 
the embassy would not comment while the case is under investigation 
earlier the embassy said in a statement it had cooperated fully 
with japanese authorities 
those arrested earlier included a 43yearold woman who owns 
several small companies a 44yearold real estate firm owner the 
president of a securities firm in hong kong and a shrine employee 
uranium must be enriched to serve as nuclear fuel because in its 
natural state it lacks an adequate concentration of a fissionable 
material known as isotope u235 
an analysis by the science and technology agency showed the 
sample taken to the embassy contained 07 percent u235 
nuclear experts say nuclear power generation needs uranium 
containing more than 3 percent u235 and a nuclear bomb needs 
uranium that contains more than 90 percent u235 
violation of uranium handling provisions in japans nuclear 
safety laws carries a penalty of up to a year in prison or a fine of 
up to 3500 
