so far only by the bahamas and china 
i hope the convention will come into force by early next year 
pending its ratification by at least 20 nations said margaret j 
anstee directorgeneral of the un office in vienna where a un 
conference on drugs opened monday 
the treaty calls for extradition of accused drug traffickers and 
the exchange of law enforcement information it also lifts bank 
secrecy provisions to aid authorities in tracking money laundering 
mandates that commercial carriers ensure their cargoes are free of 
drugs and requires supervision of the production and sale of 
chemicals used in the manufacture of illegal drugs 
it also has provisions that allow governments to seize assets of 
drug traffickers 
the legislatures of at least 20 nations must ratify the 
convention for it to go into effect in the united states the 
treaty is pending in the senate 
ms anstee said the proposed un convention against illicit 
traffic in narcotic drugs and psychotropic substances which was 
signed in vienna in december would provide a powerful weapon to 
combat drug abuse 
these countries have to readjust their laws to comply with the 
conventions requirements and that takes a little time she said 
in an interview during the drug conference 
the fiveday conference has been dominated by developments in 
colombia where the government is waging a nationwide crackdown on 
its powerful cocaine cartels 
ms anstee said the conference would result in a resolution 
supporting the colombian government delegates from nearly 100 
nations are attending 
</TEXT>
