at least 16 tanker crew members have 
been stopped from boarding their vessels at the oil shipment 
terminal in valdez since june because they had been drinking 
authorities said wednesday 
the alcohol screening program was set up in response to the 
grounding of the tanker exxon valdez which hit a reef hours after 
it left the terminal said george jurkowich a spokesman for alyeska 
pipeline service co 
the exxon valdez dumped almost 11 million gallons of thick north 
slope crude oil in prince william sound on march 24 in the nations 
worst oil spill 
the captain joseph hazelwood was tested hours after the 
accident and alcohol was found in his system 
crew members who go ashore while their tankers are in port pass 
through security at the alyeska terminal before reboarding they are 
given breath tests if it appears to security guards they have been 
drinking jurkowich said 
all ships masters are tested before their vessels leave the 
terminal complex jurkowich said 
between the time the screening system was set up june 1 and 
friday 1087 crew members have passed through the terminal 56 have 
been tested and 16 have been foud to have unacceptable levels of 
alcohol jurkowich said they were prevented from boarding their 
ships 
we think it is a success because we are detecting a small 
percentage of people who are under the influence he said if a 
crewman leaves his vessel leaves the terminal when they come 
back to the terminal they are required to pass through alyeskas 
security office 
jurkowich said the bloodalcohol level of crew members must be 
below 04 percent that is the coast guards highest allowable level 
for operation of a commercial vessel 
the state of alaska and many other states consider motorists 
drunk if they have a bloodalcohol level of 10 
if a crew member fails he must wait an hour and be retested 
its up to the ships owner or agent to determine what happens to 
a crew member who isnt allowed aboard the tanker 
