spills of toxic materials on railroads rose by 
13 percent in 1988 but highway incidents dropped a private group 
reported wednesday 
citizen action citing statistics from the transportation 
department said there were 1015 toxic spills on railroads last 
year the most since the department started keeping track of such 
incidents in 1982 
an industry representative however disputed the significance of 
many of the spills cited by citizen action and accused the group of 
trying to cloud railroad safety 
there were no deaths linked to the spills but they caused nine 
major injuries and 27 minor ones and resulted in 24 million in 
damage citizen action said 
texas led the nation with 151 incidents followed by ohio 64 
illinois 59 and georgia 55 the group said 
this growing list of railroad catastrophes and 
nearcatastrophes is no aberation citizen action said rather 
it is the inevitable consequence of the increased reliance on the 
rail transport of toxic chemicals explosives combustibles 
caustics and other hazardous materials 
the totals included small spills that may have been related to a 
broken valve on a rail car or other faulty equipment said robert 
creamer a citizen action spokesman 
there were 4831 highway incidents in 1988 a drop from 4932 
recorded in 1987 citizen action said 
the transportation department data are based only on incidents 
reported to the government and as a consequence are very 
conservative the group said 
but jim reiter a spokesman for the association of american 
railroads said many of the spills counted by citizen action were 
small and occurred in rail yards he said there were 44 major train 
accidents that caused spills down from 50 in 1987 
railroad companies moved 14 million carloads of hazardous 
materials last year he said 
