<TEXT>
the house passed legislation wednesday to 
outlaw the trading practices cited in a wave of indictments 
involving the nations two largest futures exchanges in chicago 
the commodity futures improvements act which passed 420to0 
also would give extra muscle to the commodity futures trading 
commission which congressional critics have called too gentle a 
watchdog of the nations futures markets 
the legislation makes sweeping changes in trading practices 
exposed in last months indictments of 45 brokers and traders and a 
clerk at the chicago mercantile exchange and the chicago board of 
trade 
the bill would 
ban insider trading on the nations 13 active futures exchanges 
require floor traders those who trade only for themselves and 
not for outside customers to register with the cftc 
limit trading among broker associations that could conflict with 
customers accounts 
severely restrict the practice of dual trading 
in dual trading floor traders on an exchange can trade for 
themselves as well as their customers on the same day 
while not illegal the practice has raised conflictofinterest 
questions about whether traders take care of themselves ahead of 
their customers supporters of the practice say it is necessary to 
maintain market liquidity when there are few customer orders 
the bill also requires exchanges to maintain accurate trading 
records so that investigators can reconstruct any given transaction 
the chicago indictments included numerous charges of customers 
defrauded through falsified trading records transactions on the 
chicago exchanges as well as others around the country use 
handwritten paper cards to record sales and purchases with the 
trader entering the information 
within weeks of the indictments the two chicago exchanges 
announced they were working to develop handheld computer terminals 
to record floor trading 
the bill would require exchanges one year after enactment to 
develop systems that would pinpoint the time of a trades execution 
to within one minute of its occurrence 
that standard would be tightened to 30 seconds within three years 
of enactment 
the bill also would make permanent the cftc which which congress 
has reauthorized on a temporary basis every three or four years 
since it was created in 1974 
the senate has yet to take up the cftcs reauthorization but sen 
patrick leahy dvt and chairman of the senate agriculture 
committee said last week that he was asking staff members to draw 
up legislation to correct gaps in the agencys surveillance of 
trading activities 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

