<DOCNO> AP890913-0247 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a solution has been found to one of the most 
distressing events in the life of smallbusiness founders and 
operators one that allows them to have their company and financial 
security too 
it turns what could have been a sad event into a triumph one 
that in many instances produces a winwinwin situation involving a 
relieved seller a happy buyer and satisfied lenders 
the event develops when a founder must sell out to raise funds 
perhaps to finance eventual retirement traditionally more than 
only a business is sold in the package also are skills hopes and 
sweat that built it 
even more the company a monument to the founder and 12hour 
days may be bought by a larger company that puts a less dedicated 
9to5 manager in charge sales fade in a few years the company 
disappears 
no monument no tombstone not even a memory 
sanford ziff escaped that fate which was common a few years ago 
he got full price for his 100unit retail chain put money in the 
bank remained in control provided for his sons participation 
received funds to expand and obtained an investment in a 
firstclass rationally structured company 
that or other seemingly impossible feats is the combined result 
of more creative lending itself a consequence of bank deregulation 
more enterprising investment groups and ingenious 
boutiqueinvestment advisers 
alan k wells who helped put the ziff deal together is one 
acting for the seller his firm bollinger wells lett amp co brings 
the parties together determines the needs of each and somehow 
merges the different interests 
its a touchy timeconsuming business involving intimate 
knowledge of the sellers needs the interests of potential buyers 
and the possibilities for creative financing it involves no 
boilerplate each deal is unique 
overly simplified a price perhaps 20 million is set by wells 
and the seller wells already has a list of investment groups that 
might consider the deal one is acceptable with wells the parties 
sit down to discussions 
you never know the shape of the table in advance says wells 
he and his client at one moment might be confronting the buyer but 
shortly thereafter joining the buyer as an investor in the new 
capitalized company 
the buyer and its investors often including wells his client 
and maybe some of the clients family seek financing generally 
they put up a relatively small amount borrowing the rest 
that small investment however can capture sizeable ownership 
the reason because the recapitalization involves large amounts of 
debt the equity value of the company shrinks perhaps from 20 
million to 1 million 
therefore to buy 10 percent of the financially restructured 
company costs only 100000 which generally makes the 
entrepreneurseller happy 
it should the entrepreneur gets liquidity estate planning and 
assured survival of his heritage he or she keeps ongoing control of 
the future without great personal risk because much of the risk has 
been transferred to lenders 
and wells insists freed from worries protected from lenders 
by covenants the entrepreneur becomes a better manager able to 
concentrate on expanding the market which he knows rather than 
tedious backoffice details 
others are happy too says wells lender and buyer get good 
management and participation in a company with cash flow to handle 
repayments and growth to retire debt lenders get a good return and 
maybe the chance to convert debt to equity as the company grows 
wells says the process beats the way deals were done just five 
years ago then he says small companies simply were bought out by 
large companies in two years the manager was gone five years 
later the company was gone 
now he says the manager and his family have liquidity key 
employees have stock control is retained and recapitalized the 
company leaps the divide that keeps small companies from growing 
large 
</TEXT>
