<TEXT>
the international tug of war over the british 
conglomerate bat industries plc lurched back to capitol hill with a 
top senate republican urging the bush administration to stay out of 
the takeover fight 
sen bob packwood of oregon in a letter to secretary of state 
james a baker disclosed tuesday said the us government should 
take no action to avoid the appearance of unreasonable 
government interference 
packwood ranking minority member of the senate finance 
committee sent similar letters to treasury secretary nicholas 
brady us trade representative carla hills and securities and 
exchange commission chairman david s ruder 
ruder has already informed several congressmen that the sec does 
not believe it has the authority to do more than monitor the 
takeover bid for bat which owns several major us companies 
the packwood letter was the latest development in an 
international legal and public relations tug of war since hoylake 
investments ltd a consortium headed by anglofrench financier sir 
james goldsmith launched a 21 billion bid for bat the worlds 
largest tobacco company in late july 
bat whose us holdings include brown amp williamson tobacco 
corp the saks fifth avenue and marshall field department stores 
and farmers insurance group has vowed to fight the unsought 
takeover 
packwoods sept 6 letter was in sharp contrast to a letter sent 
to baker last month cosigned by more than 200 members of the house 
and senate asking him to express their concern to the british 
government about the multinational leveraged buyout 
senate aides who spoke on condition that they not be identified 
said packwood wrote the letter on his own and it did not reflect the 
views of other republicans on the committee 
because goldsmith has a reputation for taking over companies and 
then breaking them up and selling off the pieces labor unions in 
this country have condemned the takeover as a potential threat to 
about 55000 us workers 
and 209 members of congress both democrats and republicans 
