<TEXT>
two partners in the accounting giant coopers amp 
lybrand say they will appeal an order barring them from practicing 
before the securities and exchange commission for the next five 
years 
an administrative judge in a ruling announced tuesday found 
david j checkosky and norman a aldrich had engaged in blatant 
serious unprofessional conduct 
following 30 days of hearings 13 witnesses and 350 exhibits the 
administrative judge ruled in favor of the sec which claimed 
checkosky and aldrich violated generally accepted standards of 
auditing and principles of accounting in audits their firm did for 
savin corp which markets copy machines 
financial information provided in the audits portrayed the 
company as a far more successful business enterprise than it was 
according to the judges ruling 
its fair to characterize the judges decision as outrageous 
said geoffrey f aronow an attorney for both men who worked in 
coopers amp lybrands stamford conn headquarters 
aronow accused the administrative judge brenda p murray of of 
ignoring large portions of the evidence in the record and said 
she has misapplied the applicable auditing principles and 
misconstrued the underlying regulatory legal standards that apply 
here 
he said his clients intend to appeal to the commission and 
believe the propriety of their actions will ultimately be 
vindicated 
there were no allegations of wrongdoing against savin in the sec 
action but several investors lawsuits are pending in connecticut 
a spokesman for coopers amp lybrand was not available for comment 
savin has been a client of coopers amp lybrand one of the nations 
largest accounting firms since the mid1960s 
the judge noted that annual billings from savin totaled about 
340000 
for professional reasons it was important to both men that the 
client be pleased with their efforts unfortunately pleasing the 
client became their paramount consideration she wrote in a 
68page opinion 
checkosky and aldrich were the senior people assigned to the 
savin audits in question for fiscal years 1981 through 1984 
savins fiscal year ran from may 1 to april 30 
the sec charged among other things that the two partners did 
not adequately plan the audits did not exercise due care in 
examining savin financial statements and did not obtain sufficient 
credible evidence to back up the opinions they submitted in sec 
documents 
according to the judges finding the partners wrongly claimed it 
was proper to defer as startup costs the costs savin incurred in 
developing a new copier 
she found the secs evidence persuasive that during the time 
covered by the audits savin should have listed its costs as 
research and development expenses 
by deferring rather than expensing savin kept these costs from 
increasing its net operating loss during the period in question 
instead these costs were included as assets on savins balance sheet 
and increased owners equity 
