<TEXT>
somewhere under the rainbow a group of 
tupperware executives broke into a song and dance about the famous 
airtight plastic containers soon some of the other 10000 top 
dealers and family members at the annual corporate jubilee took up 
the chorus 
the celebration once the premier local shindig in the days 
before the central florida themepark boom was held last month 
beneath a 120foot metal rainbow erected behind tupperware world 
headquarters 
the spot seemed appropriate for a company that spent years 
hunting for the pot of gold it lost when waves of working mothers 
and fasterpaced lifestyles made its trademark homeparty sales 
system seem like an ozzie and harriet era anachronism 
the quest to modernize may be starting to pay off for tupperware 
which is a unit of premark international inc 
after a postrecession slump in the mid1980s tupperware home 
parties last year reported sales rose to a record 9671 million 
more than 100000 independent dealers in the united states also a 
record are now out toting their wares from office conference rooms 
to daycare centers 
with more than 80 million people attending a tupperware party 
somewhere last year the company is outselling its nearest kitchen 
container rival rubbermaid inc by nearly 21 
nobody dislikes tupperware the question was how were people 
going to find the time to buy it these days said robert 
donegan vice president of marketing we may have been slower than 
others to respond to the changing lifestyles but i think weve got 
it together now 
today alternatives to the traditional twohour home parties 
account for about 25 percent of total sales of tupperware which was 
pulled from store shelves in april 1951 
dealers are now catching customers during coffee breaks and after 
work a strategy adopted by other giants of the 9 billion 
directsale industry such as avon products inc and fuller brush co 
donegan said one of the most effective new tactics is the 
rushhour party a brief display of products at a house or other 
site along commuter routes 
people dont have a lot of time now so we get right to the 
point show the product answer questions and take the order he 
said 
tupperware this month also began allowing orders by visa and 
mastercard and is testing a system to ship products directly to 
customers rather than via the longer route from distributor to 
dealer 
later this year it may air television spots to show consumers 
how to get in touch with dealers 
since the company began phasing out references to its burp 
seal in 1979 more contemporary pastel and earthtone colors have 
been emphasized and smaller containers emerged to handle leftovers 
of singles and oneparent families 
yet one of the most popular of the nearly 200 products remains 
the original bell tumbler one of 24 tupperware pieces in the 
permanent collection of the museum of modern art in new york 
our products are timeless were just trying to stay up with 
the times in the way we make them available said tupperware 
spokeswoman lawrie pitcher platt 
its also a different brand of sales people although virtually 
all the 350000 independent dealers and distributors worldwide are 
still women the days have passed when tupperware attracted 
housewives with time on their hands but little outside work 
experience many of the new tupperware dealers in the united states 
are college educated and seeking a parttime job or the freedom of 
independent sales 
it looked for a while like we were in big trouble but these 
new women really figured out how to get out there and sell said 
tom damigella 74 an everett massbased distributor who helped 
tupperware founder earl tupper develop the home party concept in the 
late 1940s we got some real bright women out there for us now 
the seed for the tupperware empire was a lump of black 
polyethylene slag a petroleum byproduct tupper a selfeducated 
chemist and tinkerer developed a process to purify the goop into a 
tough yet flexible translucent plastic 
tupper found the nonporous plastic was perfect for food storage 
the airtight seal was modeled after a paint can lid in reverse by 
1945 tupper corp products were appearing in stores but public 
acceptance was slow and consumers were stumped by the seal 
damigella and brownie wise who both sold stanley tools and other 
home products on a home party plan worked with tupper to develop 
its party plan which was nearly unaltered until sales began to drop 
in 1983 
tupper who died in 1983 had sold the company in 1958 to rexall 
drug and chemical co which 11 years later was renamed dart 
industries inc tupperware became a unit of premark international in 
june 1986 when dart amp kraft inc a successor to dart industries 
separated its holdings 
in its 39nation market tupperware has tried to meet some unique 
demands in latin america it produces a tortilla holder japanese 
customers can order a kimono storage bin presently studies are 
under way for possible expansion into china and the soviet union 
but there are no plans to bring tupperware back to stores after 
38 years 
theres sort of a mystique to tupperware and the fact you cant 
just go out and buy it said donegan holding one of the bell 
tumblers the company is a little like the product we may have 
changed a bit over the years but the basic formula doesnt change 
</TEXT>
