cotton futures prices skyrocketed wednesday on the new york 
cotton exchange climbing as much as 2 cents a pound the permitted 
daily limit on fresh signs of shrinking world supplies 
on other markets grain and soybean futures fell steeply most 
energy futures advanced and precious metals livestock and meat 
futures were mixed 
cotton futures settled 113 cents to 2 cents higher with the 
contract for delivery in october at 7377 cents a pound 
the rally was rooted partly in tuesdays agriculture department 
crop report which painted an ultimately bullish scenario for 
cotton although it was not apparent at first blush 
for starters the usda estimated the 1989 cotton crop at 1228 
million bales which represents a 20 percent decline from the 1988 
harvest but an increase of 450000 bales from the agencys august 
estimate 
the estimate was higher than expected which would have been a 
bearish signal except that the usda also reduced by 400000 bales 
its estimate of the us cotton stockpile as of last july 31 
offsetting the increased harvest projection 
the bullish news came in the usdas new projection for world 
cotton stocks as of next july 1 252 million bales 1 million less 
than the agency had predicted a month earlier 
world supplies are dwindling analysts said because of poor 
growing weather both in the united states and abroad 
the foreign crops are not doing well especially in china and 
the soviet union said ernest simon cotton specialist in new york 
with prudentialbache securities inc 
the us crop which was punished earlier this year by too much 
rain in the southeast and too little in texas has been taking 
another beating this week due to cold wet weather in the high 
plains of texas 
prospects for at least another day of harsh weather contributed 
to cottons rally 
grain and soybean futures fell sharply on the chicago board of 
trade in selling sparked by a higher 1989 wheat crop estimate and 
expectations for an increase in 1990 wheat acreage 
the usda raised its projection for the 1989 wheat harvest to 206 
billion bushels from 204 billion surprising traders who had 
expected little change in the number 
further selling was linked to persistent rumors that the 
agriculture department is preparing to revise its 1990 wheat program 
to allow farmers to increase spring wheat planting which is already 
underway by as much as 10 million acres 
walter spilka an analyst in new york with smith barney harris 
upham amp co said that despite the improved 1989 harvest outlook 
us wheat stocks are relatively low 
he said usda leaders are worried the united states may have to 
reduce its wheat exports unless it can ensure an increase in 
supplies 
wheat futures settled 8 cents to 14 cents lower with september at 
385 a bushel corn was 2 cents to 5 cents lower with september 
at 233 a bushel oats were 2 cents to 4 cents lower with 
september at 134 a bushel soybeans were 5 cents to 15 cents 
lower with september at 586 a bushel 
