<TEXT>
an aide to us commerce secretary robert mosbacher 
denied wednesday that the white house had reprimanded mosbacher for 
his plan to promote a us highdefinition television industry 
earlier a congressional source in washington said the white 
house branded mosbacher a renegade promoting industrial policy 
with his plan to loosen tax and antitrust laws to boost the 
competitiveness of us industry in the development of 
highdefinition television or hdtv the source spoke on condition 
of anonymity 
wayne l berman counsellor to mosbacher attributed the report 
to anonymous midgets in the seat of the mighty in the white house 
commenting on matters to which they were clearly not a party 
berman accompanying mosbacher on a 15day visit to asia and 
eastern europe said the report of the reprimand was based on 
wholly incorrect information 
he said that in many months of meetings with various government 
agencies the commerce departments plan to deal with hdtv has been 
broadened 
it took us some time to evolve our thinking but we decided we 
dont want to single out hdtv for special treatment berman said 
it will be part of a larger policy to make our high technology 
competitive 
also wednesday mosbacher told japanese and foreign reporters at 
a luncheon that the flow of hdtv technology from japan the pioneer 
in the field to the united states would be welcome 
we dont believe its the governments position to take the 
lead in this kind of development but this could be a good example 
of building a basis for some technology from japan to the united 
states mosbacher said 
japans public broadcasting organization nhk said wednesday it 
will sell some of its hdtv technology to texas instruments inc so 
the us company can design chips for advanced televisions 
the congressional source had said the white house reined in 
mosbacher for talking in terms reminiscent of the industrial 
policy program that democratic presidential candidate michael 
dukakis advocated in the 1988 campaign 
the wall street journal last month quoted sources who said 
mosbachers hdtv initiative was soundly criticized by other 
government agencies and was near death 
advocates of hdtv which promises motionpicture clarity and 
compact discquality sound say it could revitalize a lifeless us 
consumer electronics industry and have important applications in 
medicine defense and other industries 
</TEXT>
