<TEXT>
american continental corp and de laurentiis 
entertainment group will be suspended from trading on the pacific 
stock exchange subject to a sept 28 vote by the exchanges 
directors an exchange spokesman said wednesday 
the exchanges equities listing committee voted tuesday to 
suspend the companies because they failed to file financial forms 
within the required 45 days of the previous quarter said spokesman 
roy berces 
the suspension will be enforced as long as they do not meet our 
listing requirements he said 
in april phoenixbased american continental a real estate and 
savings and loan holding company filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy 
protection federal regulators then seized its largest subsidiary 
lincoln savings amp loan based in irvine calif 
the collapse of lincoln could result in the governments most 
costly bailout requiring more than 25 billion in federal funds 
analysts and regulators said 
jim feder an attorney representing american continental said 
wednesday that the company to the best of his knowledge was not 
behind in its filings he referred further questions to another 
lawyer for the company who did not immediately return phone calls 
wednesday evening 
de laurentiis entertainment based in beverley hills has been 
operating under chapter 11 since august 1988 its stock was taken 
off the american stock exchange last month de laurentiis general 
counsel robert goldsmith said 
goldsmith acknowledged that the company no longer met the 
exchanges requirements for net worth and conducting an ongoing 
business shareholders of deg stock are unlikely to receive anything 
for their shares he said 
carolco pictures inc and italian financier giancarlo parretti 
have been conducting a bidding war for what remains of the company 
which was founded by dino de laurentiis the italian movie producer 
the forms the companies failed to file were 10q forms similar 
to quarterly reports and 10k forms similar to yearend reports 
berces said 
</TEXT>
